Subject: Details on Maintenance and PLM Effort for Zabbix

Dear [Recipient's Name],

Thank you for your query regarding the time spent on maintenance and PLM for Zabbix. Please find below a detailed summary of our activities and efforts:

1. Scheduled Auto Patching
Scheduled auto-patching is enabled for all our Zabbix internal servers. This process runs automatically on a monthly basis based on the patching cycle selected during server provisioning, requiring minimal manual effort.


2. Daily Automated Health Checks
We perform automated server health checks twice daily. Reports are sent to our mailbox, and any abnormalities are addressed promptly.


3. Quarterly High-Availability Checks
Every quarter, we perform high-availability checks by switching nodes. This activity typically requires 2 to 3 hours to complete.


4. Progress on PLM for Servers

As of now, we have completed PLM for 16+ servers, including both staging and production environments.

PLM for 9 servers is pending and will be addressed post-peak season.



5. Planned Zabbix Agent IP Change Activity
For changing the IP in the Zabbix agent configuration across 2000+ servers, we are exploring two approaches:
a) Deploying new proxies and, with the network team's assistance, swapping the current proxy IP with the new proxy to avoid individual server updates. (Feasibility is under review.)
b) If approach (a) is not feasible, we will schedule a call with the application team and, using a CR, update the IP in the Zabbix agent config via Ansible in a single operation. We plan to use DNS instead of IP to reduce future effort.
Timeline: The exact timeline will depend on the network team's validation of approach (a).


6. Automated Configuration and Database Backup

Zabbix configuration backups are automated weekly.

Sequential and full database backups are performed as per DBA guidelines since the backend DB is managed by the DBA team.



7. Partitioning for Larger Tables

Partitioning was implemented on larger tables in our production Zabbix instance during an upgrade on October 19th.

Old history data is purged every 3 months, and trend data every year, helping manage storage costs.

Validation of this automated process takes approximately 2 to 3 hours monthly.



8. Custom Module Development

Leveraging Zabbix's open-source nature, we spend about 2 to 3 hours weekly developing and integrating custom modules based on requirements.



9. Testing New Release Functionalities

Testing new functionalities provided by Zabbix during release cycles takes approximately 4 to 5 hours monthly.




I hope this provides clarity on our maintenance and PLM efforts. Please let me know if you need further details or specific timelines for any activities.

